@node "howto" "How do I use this program?"

         @{b}Controls@{ub}

------------------------

-------Mouse Controls

-----------------------

Any Time:

   - Close window gadget to exit.


During the Intro:

   - Click in the window to skip the intro.


Main Section:

   - Click the menu options for selections.  (adding actual gadgets soon (c;  )


Cards are being displayed:

   - Click on whichever card you want to read.

   - Click in the lower area, and it will return to the menu.



------------------------

-------Keyboard Controls

------------------------

When intro is playing:


   any key        - proceeds directly to the menu


When the main menu is displayed:


   a or A         - prepares for the 3 card layout

   b or B         - prepares for the keltic method

   q or Q         - exits the program



When the card drawings are being displayed:


   # keys         - selects card with matching number

   q or Q         - returns to the main menu

   ESC            - returns to the main menu


When the card text is being displayed:


   Card window Close Gadget   - closes the card window

   any keypress               - closes the card window


@endnode
@node "inter" "How do I interpret these cards?"

     @{b}Interpreting the meaning@{ub}


The following are not my words at all, they are excerpts from:

Eden Gray, @{u}A Complete Guide to the Tarot@{uu} New York:Bantam Books ©1970-1986




HOW TO PREPARE YOURSELF


   Do not encourage levity in those present, for a reading is a serious attempt to go above the
psychic realm to a higher level where the Truth is accessible.
   I would advise that you do not take the first few of your readings too seriously.  In reading for
yourself, be particularly careful that a  happy mood does not incline you to over-rosy
interpretations; likewise, if you are blue and discouraged, be sure to check how much your mood is
affecting your reading.



SHUFFLING AND LAYING OUT THE CARDS


   You are called the Reader, and the person for whom you are going to read is the Querent.
   It is best to have the Querent shuffle the deck, but if this seems impractical, the Reader may do
so, asking the Querent to lay his(/her) hands on the deck before cutting.  While shuffling, the
Querent should ask, silently, a simple but important question, repeating it over and over again
mentally until he(/she) feels the question has entered the cards.  It is best if the Reader does not
know what the question is, since this knowledge might color the reading unduly.  During the shuffling
the Reader should silently ask that only the highest forces surround them.  Later, when the reading
is nearly finished, the question can be told and the cards then gone over for amplification.



THE LAYOUT


   Glance quickly at all the cards laid out, and note if there is a perponderance of any one suit or
if there are many Court cards or cards of the Major Arcana.  These will indicate a general trend or
direction in the readings.


       Many Wands - @{i}Change@{ui}

        Many Cups - @{i}Love, goodness@{ui}

      Many Swords - @{i}Strife@{ui}

   Many Pentacles - @{i}Political action or intrigue@{ui}


The presence of many of the Major Arcana indicates that the answer to the Querent's question is
largely controlled by other people.

   Remember that the readings depend not only on the meaning of the individual card but also on its
place in the layout, and that the cards on each side may also affect the interpretation.

   Questions usually fall into one of the fillowing categories:


1. Love, Marriage, Family situations

2. Money, Business affairs, Property

3. Personal accomplishment, Travel

4. States of mind, Problems encountered on the spiritual plane



HOW TO INTERPRET THE CARDS


   Try to make a running story about what you see in the cards in relation to the person for whom you
are reading.  If you have forgotten the meanings of some of the cards, look them up--don't guess.


   If, after reading the cards, the Querent tells you that the question is not answered, ask him if the
cards have perhaps dealt with a deeper question that he has been worrying about.  I have found that
people are sometimes a little timid about bringing out into the open what is really on their minds,
and will ask a superficial question of the Tarot.  With a little digging and a sincere desire to
help, you may uncover what is really bothering the Querent and find that the cards have indeed
answered a question that really was uppermost in his mind.


   Sometimes the cards do not seem to be responding at all.  In that case, ask the Querent to shuffle
again and concentrate more deeply on the question.  If, on reshuffling, the cards still do not make
sense, it would be well to put them away for at least twenty-four hours before trying to read them
again.


   NEVER, NEVER, NEVER finish the reading on a discouraging note.  If the cards are bad, indicate how
the Querent can overcome the problems by work, study, application to tasks, better care of health, or
by expending more love and compassion in relationships.  You may foretell--but only in a vague
manner--the possible illness or death of someone the Querent knows, but @{i}never predict a serious
illness or death for the Querent@{ui}.  Instead, say you see the possibility of a slight illness in
the future, which could be avoided if the Querent would take better care of his health, and then
quickly move on to interpreting a more positive section of the layout.


   Reading the Tarot is a great responsibility.  It gives you the opportunity to help others gain an
insight into what may be holding them back from their fullest self-expression.  Other people are as
sensitive as you are, and giving a discouraging reading with no hope held out for the future is a
cruel and pointless thing to do.  Besides, we have all seen seemingly hopeless lives suddenly take
remarkable turns for the better.  While there is life, there is always hope.


   So, now you are on your own, to use your new skill with good taste and delicacy.  For all its
seriousness the Tarot can be fun--so enjoy it!


--end of quoting... that is all from pages 147 - 151


   I didn't type every single paragraph, because some only apply to actually having a deck and shuffling
in your hands.  And others just don't quite fit with an electronic version of Tarot either.

@endnode
